What is Data Analysis?

Data Analysis means understanding data before building a Machine Learning model.

It helps us:

Understand data distribution
Find relationships between variables
Detect outliers
Find patterns
Choose suitable ML algorithms
1. Univariate Analysis
Definition

Univariate Analysis means analyzing only one variable (one column) at a time.

"Uni" = One

Goal

Understand the distribution of a single feature.

Questions answered
What are the values?
What is the average?
Is the data skewed?
Are there outliers?
What is the spread?
Example

Dataset

Age
18
20
22
24
25

Only Age is analyzed.

Numerical Features

For numerical columns we calculate:

Mean
Median
Mode
Minimum
Maximum
Range
Variance
Standard Deviation
Percentiles

Visualization:

Histogram
Box Plot
Distribution Plot
Categorical Features

Example:

Gender

Male
Female
Male
Male
Female

Visualization:

Count Plot
Bar Chart
Pie Chart (less preferred)
Why Univariate Analysis?

It helps us

Understand feature distribution
Detect missing values
Detect outliers
Check skewness
Decide preprocessing techniques
2. Bivariate Analysis
Definition

Bivariate Analysis means analyzing two variables together.

"Bi" = Two

Goal:
Find the relationship between two variables.

Questions answered
Does one variable affect another?
Are they positively related?
Are they negatively related?
Is there any correlation?
Example
Hours Studied	Marks
2	40
4	60
6	75
8	90

As study hours increase,
marks also increase.

Positive Relationship.

Numerical vs Numerical

Examples

Height vs Weight

Salary vs Experience

Visualization

Scatter Plot
Line Plot

Statistical Measure

Correlation
Numerical vs Categorical

Examples

Salary vs Gender

Age vs Survival

Visualization

Box Plot
Violin Plot
Categorical vs Categorical

Examples

Gender vs Purchased

Branch vs Placement

Visualization

Count Plot
Crosstab
Heatmap
3. Multivariate Analysis
Definition

Multivariate Analysis means analyzing more than two variables together.

"Multi" = Many

Goal:
Understand how multiple features interact.

Example

Predicting House Price using

Area
Bedrooms
Location
Parking
Age of House

Instead of one feature,
many features are used together.

Visualization
Pair Plot
Heatmap
3D Scatter Plot
Correlation Matrix
Why Multivariate Analysis?

It helps us

Find feature interactions
Detect multicollinearity
Select important features
Improve model accuracy
Real ML Example

Suppose you want to predict whether a passenger survives on the Titanic.

Features:

Age
Sex
Fare
Passenger Class
Embarked

Analysis performed:

Univariate: Distribution of Age.
Bivariate: Age vs Survival, Sex vs Survival.
Multivariate: Age + Sex + Fare + Pclass → Survival.

This is exactly the process followed before training the ML model.

Interview Questions
Q1. What is Univariate Analysis?

Answer: Analyzing a single variable to understand its distribution, central tendency, spread, and outliers.

Q2. What is Bivariate Analysis?

Answer: Analyzing two variables together to study their relationship or association.

Q3. What is Multivariate Analysis?

Answer: Analyzing three or more variables simultaneously to understand complex relationships and interactions.

Q4. Give one example of each.

Univariate: Age distribution

Bivariate: Hours Studied vs Marks

Multivariate: House Price prediction using Area, Bedrooms, Location, and Age of House
